Q6: 1,2,5,6,7,8, This sums it up best: Friends and family:    I hope that this finds everyone of you safe and healthy at this tragic time.  Some reading this are people from my past, and I hope no offense is taken in our lost connection or my unexpected outreach.  Some of you maybe had limited contact and were in my contact list but the sentiment is the same for everyone.  I don't mean to get political, preach, scold, or upset anyone so I apologize if it's taken that way.      I, as we all are, am struggling with decisions I never wanted to have to make. I haven’t hugged my wife or kids for over a week. (extra space) My mom spent her 73rd birthday alone because we are all a risk to each other right now. At least 90% of my appointments have been canceled, and I will only have someone come to my office if virtual visits or waiting this out aren't justifiable options.  I have also canceled surgeries knowing that those patients are going to suffer in the short term and likely have a more difficult treatment and recovery in the future for an inferior but “acceptable” result, all this in the name of giving all of us a better chance of surviving this nightmare.   It’s a simple reality of the present: Bringing people together where an alternative exists will unnecessarily lead to and prolong human suffering.    Bold, decisive, and unselfish changes today will directly result in less disease transmission and, more importantly, less people dying.  We will all be impacted by and have our impact on this in some way.  For some, that can mean unintentionally aiding the spread of the virus, which can exponentially increase with devastating outcomes.  In many cases, this will be through interaction that wasn't absolutely essential but is continued out of complacency, convenience, or greed.       Every one of us should have the bare minimum of personal contacts and encourage/implore the same of those around us.  Unless it's truly impossible, don't see your parents, adult kids, or friends, don't have any person who doesn't live with you enter your house (maids, nannies, maintenance), only interact with people you don't live with while outside and at a distance whenever possible, kids from different households playing, even outside, should not be allowed.       If you do have to leave your home to work or have no choice but to have indoor interactions, protect your own family by separating your living space as much as you can, being aware of every surface you touch, and keeping physical distance at all times.  Any business that requires entering another person's home should only be provided on an emergency basis.  If your business depends on this in-home activity, protect yourself, your employees, and your customers by only performing work that, with complete objectivity, can't wait 8-12 weeks.      Regardless of the expanded financial impact and subsequent fear that would result, more definitive and bold measures to define and streamline access to what is truly essential will reduce infections and save lives.  We have clear basic essentials that I recognize still require a lot of human activity and interaction to support our communities.  However, we don't need every bank branch, restaurant, liquor store, convenience store, coffee shop, pot dispensary, or hardware store to remain open to provide these essentials.   Consolidation and creativity are needed..   Our corporations and our government can allow and enforce significantly more remote work than many already have.  I value my freedom as much as the next person, but rational and specific public health and safety decisions need to trump (no pun intended, just the appropriate word) ego, financial consequences, and sensitivity at this time.     I know many of us, through optimism, convenience, complacency, or misinformation, are not sufficiently heeding the warnings.  Social distancing is a meme at this point. We may reason with ourselves that people can stay at a safe distance within an office or store, but it simply ignores the reality that this requires people to share sinks, doorknobs, pens, telephones, bathrooms, refrigerators, and, most importantly, the same air. This virus is clearly being transmitted in ways we haven't yet controlled, and extreme caution is justified.      I hope all of you and those you love will stay safe and remain as productive as you can through this hopefully once-in-a-lifetime world tragedy.     Every moment counts.  Keep your circle small.  The more serious we take this, and the more people we make aware of their relaxed but unwittingly dangerous actions, the better off we will all be on the other side.     With hope for health, prosperity, and happiness,
